    {
      "id": 40,
      "type": "text",
      "title": "Coverage & gaps",
      "gridPos": { "h": 7, "w": 24, "x": 0, "y": 39 },
      "options": {
        "mode": "markdown",
        "content": "**What this harness proves (per cycle, from Prometheus only):** intent-match (charge/discharge/idle), setpoint delta (kW), source-class inputs parity (primary vs degraded), and charge-guard conflict — joining zeus's LIVE `zeus_*` against the tervuren lar's SHADOW `jupiter_lar_*`, keyed on `site_id`.\n\n**`jupiter_shadow_logic_divergence` is the P4 cutover gate:** intents differ *while metric-visible inputs agree*. Sustained 0 across a soak = the shadow logic matches the live logic = safe to flip the site live.\n\n**Partial — `inputs_equal` attribution:** only the source *class* is compared here (the zeus enum has 5 codes, the lar 3, so raw-code equality would be wrong). The fine-grained fingerprint — `price_curve_etag`, `forecast_trained_at`, `running_peak_kw`, and SoC equality — lives ONLY in the retained MQTT plan doc `jupiter/<site>/plan`, which is not scraped. So a \"logic\" flag here means *logic OR a same-class-but-different-curve/SoC input*. Tightening to full inputs-equality needs an MQTT consumer (follow-up).\n\n**One-sided signals:** the lar exposes no guard-trip or SoC metric yet (guard counters land with jupiter #137; SoC is MQTT-only). Guard-conflict is inferred from zeus's guard trips vs the lar's charge intent."
      }
    }
